In addressing the members of one’s own family it was ¹ customary to add Suo (or Suae), eg. Tullius Terentiae Suae S. P! (ie. salutem plurimam). After this address there often appeared some formula like si vales, bene est, either written out in full or in the abbreviation s. v. b. e. ors. v. b. (ie. benest).⁹ Cicero himself rarely used this formula.¹⁰

In writing to the members of one's own household, appar- ently some closing formula was ordinarily used. Such formulae are found at the end of all the letters to Terentia and to Tiro.
